CreditLine: Acquired by Henry Walters with the Massarenti Collection, 1902
Description: Weight is on the right leg, the right hand is at the side holding the thunderbolt and the left is raised in the position for holding a staff. The thunderbolt seems to have one screw end. A chlamys is thrown over the left shoulder and upper arm, and falls to the back and front. The head is bearded and turns slightly to the right. A protuberance at the front of the head shows that there was some sort of diadem or garland; ribbons from the end of this ornament reach the shoulders.
Provenance: Don Marcello Massarenti Collection, Rome [date and mode of acquisition unknown]; Henry Walters, Baltimore, 1902, by purchase; Walters Art Museum, 1931, by bequest.
Title: Jupiter (Zeus)
